      <h1> Interactive Media : Assignment 1 </h1>

      <h2> Chosen Web Project: National Gallery of Victoria </h2>

      <p> 

<a href="https://www.ngv.vic.gov.au/"> NGV website </a>

1) What was the first thing you paid attention to when interacting with the experience?
  The acknowledgement of the traditional owners for the land on which the NGV was built
  Once on the home page, it was the scrolling gallery at the header.

2) Spend two minutes with the experience and create a list of each of your discrete actions.
  - Scrolled through the displayed exhibitions and events
  - Went to the "Collection" page using the nav bar
  - Clicked on the "Takahiro Iwasaki" collection
  - Clicked through the image collection
  - Went back to the "What's On" page through the nav bar
  - Clicked on "see all exhibitions"
  - Scrolled through the page until I reached the footer
  - Clicked on "Virtual Tours"
  - Went back to the home page after browsing the displayed tours

3) What part of the experience did you spend the most time engaging with?
  Viewing the photo collections that linked to pages containing further information

4) What was the most common action in your two minute interaction with the experience?
  Scrolling or using the nav bar to navigate the site

5) What is your impression of the intended primary goal of the interactive experience?
  To show off all the avaliablee exhibitions and events (past, present and upcoming) and provide extra detail on each

6) How does the interactive experience communicate this primary goal?
  Very smoothly and efficiently, with clear grids and collections that are appropriately lablled

7) What is your impression of how the experience should be interacted with over time? (For how long and how many different times)
  To give the user a good idea of what is avaliable, with repeat visits to both the site and exhibitions, and allow them to take their time to read up on what interests them

8) How does the interactive experience communicate how it should be interacted with over time?
  Excellently, with simple images that will entice further reading or ticket bookings, where the more you browse the options, the higher chacnc you'll find what you like

9) What other media forms (digital or otherwise) does the experience reference?
  Digital images of real life art peices and places
  Some background videos displaying the art showcases

10) What does this reference/s communicate to you about how you should act when engaging with your research experience?
  Communicates what the website is advertising and what you could expect if you were to attend

11) What does this reference/s communicate to you about how you should feel when engaging with your research experience?
  If I find an event that appeals to me, I should feel intrigued to go and see the shown exhibition

12) What is the most frustrating part of the interaction to you and what makes that part frustrating?
  Too many pages, some pages while navigating the site took a while to load and hence dappened my experience

13) What is the most satisfying part of the interaction to you and what makes that part satisfying?
  The auto scrolling collections and auto playing videos made for a more lively site

